{
  "id": 132837,
  "referenceId": 108891,
  "name": "Romans 6:1–23",
  "localizedName": "Romans 6:1–23",
  "content": [
    {
      "tiptap": {
        "type": "doc",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "People shouldn’t use God’s grace as an excuse to continue sinning. Jesus saves people from slavery to sin and death."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "As a sign that they are saved, believers are "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108037",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "baptised"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". Going under the water is like dying and being buried with Jesus. Coming out of the water is like being raised with Christ from the dead. Believers are raised to live a new life."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The new freedom believers enjoy is based on dying to who they used to be. They used to be ruled by sin. But all their old ways are put to death on the cross with Christ. They have changed and sin no longer rules over them. They are now under God’s rule."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Paul described this as being a slave to God instead of to sin. God’s followers desire to serve him. They use their freedom to follow Jesus their Lord. They no longer want to serve sin and death. By serving Christ, his followers receive the blessing of "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108044",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "holy living"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
